Amniotic fluid is primarily formed by fetal urine, which becomes the major component as the fetus develops. The evidence explicitly states that “fetal urine comprises most of the amniotic fluid” and notes that the fluid’s composition shifts over time, increasing in substances like urea and creatinine—markers of fetal metabolism and waste. Maternal fluids contribute initially, but post-first-trimester, fetal excretion dominates. Thus, the main contributor is the fetus.

